.TH YABR 1 "2025" "yabr 1.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
yabr \- yet another bulk renamer
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B yabr
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] [\fIfile\fR ...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B yabr
is a CLI bulk rename utility that uses your text editor to rename files.
Running
.B yabr
on a directory opens your
.B $EDITOR
with a list of filenames. Edit the names, save, and quit.
.B yabr
renames everything accordingly.
.PP
.B yabr
has syntax similar to
.BR ls (1).
Running it on a single directory uses the files in that directory.
Passing multiple directories returns all their contents.
Paths are displayed relative to the least common ancestor of all sources
unless
.B \-l
is passed to display absolute paths.
.PP
.B yabr
also accepts piped input, making it compatible with
.BR find (1),
.BR grep (1),
.BR sort (1),
and other standard tools.
.SH USAGE
.SS Renaming and deleting
Files passed to
.B yabr
open in your editor. To rename a file, change its name. To delete a file,
blank out its line.
.B The total number of lines must not change.
.B yabr
will abort if any lines have been added or removed.
.PP
.B yabr
works as follows:
.IP 1. 4
Validates all sources. Sources that don't exist or lack permissions are omitted
(use
.B \-v
to see warnings, or
.B \-\-strict
to abort on any warning).
.IP 2. 4
Evaluates all changes made by the user and validates target paths and permissions.
.IP 3. 4
Previews all proposed actions. The user can then modify changes, reset to
original names, abort, or execute.
.SS Collisions
If a rename target already exists or will exist as the result of another rename,
.B yabr
prompts the user to resolve it:
.IP \(bu 4
.B Overwrite:
Overwrite the target. Suppress prompts with
.BR \-f .
.IP \(bu 4
.B Skip:
Skip the rename. Suppress prompts with
.BR \-s .
.IP \(bu 4
.B Increment:
Append an increment suffix to the target name. Suppress prompts with
.B \-i
or
.BR \-I .
.SS Path name resolution
If a rename target's parent directories do not exist,
.B yabr
will prompt the user to create them. Suppress this prompt with
.BR \-p .
.SS Deletion
Blanking a line marks that file for deletion.
.B yabr
will prompt before deleting. Suppress with
.BR \-D .
Deleting non-empty directories requires both
.B \-D
and
.BR \-f .
.SS Rename cycles
Rename cycles (e.g. A\(->B and B\(->A) are handled automatically
using temporary files.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Print help message and exit.
.TP
.B \-\-version
Print the build version and exit.
.TP
.BR \-v " [\fILEVEL\fR], " \-\-verbose "[=\fILEVEL\fR]"
Enable verbose output. Without LEVEL, defaults to 2.
0 = silent, 1 = errors only, 2 = warnings, 3 = info.
.TP
.B \-\-debug
Enable debug-level logging. Equivalent to
.BR \-\-verbose=3 .
.TP
.BR \-e ", " \-\-exec
Execute renames without preview.
.TP
.BR \-n ", " \-\-dry
Dry run. Preview changes without renaming any files. Implies verbosity level 3.
.TP
.BR \-l ", " \-\-absolute\-paths
Display absolute paths.
.TP
.BR \-a ", " \-\-show\-hidden
Include hidden files (dotfiles).
.TP
.BR \-d ", " \-\-dirs\-as\-files
Treat directories as regular files. Has no effect when combined with
.BR \-R .
.TP
.BR \-R ", " \-\-recursive
Recursively include files.
.TP
.BR \-L ", " \-\-follow\-symlinks
Follow symlinks when traversing directories.
.TP
.BR \-f ", " \-\-force
Force overwriting without prompt. Must be combined with
.B \-D
to suppress prompts for non-empty directory deletion. Mutually exclusive with
.BR \-s .
.TP
.BR \-s ", " \-\-skip
Automatically skip conflicting tasks. Mutually exclusive with
.BR \-f .
.TP
.BR \-D ", " \-\-delete
Suppress deletion prompt. Non-empty directory deletion still prompts unless
.B \-f
is also passed.
.TP
.BR \-p ", " \-\-create\-directories
Automatically create intermediate directories as required. Suppresses prompt.
.TP
.B \-\-strict
Elevate warnings to errors that immediately abort the program.
.TP
.BR \-r ", " \-\-reverse
Reverse the sorting order.
.TP
.BR \-V ", " \-\-version\-sort
Sort sources using version (natural) sort. Useful for numbered files.
.TP
.BR \-i ", " \-\-increment
Automatically increment collisions using the default format: \fBfile (1).ext\fR.
.TP
.BR \-I \fIFMT\fR ", " \-\-increment\-format= \fIFMT\fR
Same as
.B \-i
but with a custom format string where
.B %n
is replaced by the increment number.
Prepend a number for minimum digits (e.g.
.BR %3n ),
or
.B #
for automatic zero-padding based on group size (e.g.
.BR %#n ).
.TP
.BI \-\-input\-file= FILE
Rename sources using targets read from FILE, skipping the editor.
.SH INCREMENT FORMAT
The
.B \-I
flag accepts a format string containing
.BR %n :
.PP
.TS
l l.
\fBFormat\fR	\fBExample output\fR
_%n	file_1.ext, file_2.ext
_%3n	file_001.ext, file_002.ext
_%#n	auto zero-pads based on group size
 (%n)	file (1).ext (default for \-i)
.TE
.SH EXAMPLES
Rename files in a directory:
.PP
.RS
.nf
yabr ~/photos/
.fi
.RE
.PP
Recursively rename with a dry run first:
.PP
.RS
.nf
yabr \-Rn ~/project/
.fi
.RE
.PP
Rename files and auto-increment duplicates:
.PP
.RS
.nf
yabr \-i *.log
.fi
.RE
.PP
Custom increment format:
.PP
.RS
.nf
yabr \-I "_%3n" *.jpg
yabr \-I "_%#n" *.jpg
.fi
.RE
.PP
Pipe from find:
.PP
.RS
.nf
find . \-name "*.jpg" | yabr
.fi
.RE
.PP
Move files into a new directory structure:
.PP
.RS
.nf
yabr \-p *.jpg
.fi
.RE
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B EDITOR
The editor used to edit filenames. Falls back to
.B vi
on Unix and
.B notepad
on Windows if unset.
.SH NOTES
The number of lines in the editor must match the number of input files.
Do not add or remove lines.
.PP
Hidden files (dotfiles) are excluded by default. Use
.B \-a
to include them.
